&gt; &gt;Ah!
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;I was wanting to use it like:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;      assertEquals(double expected, double actual);
&gt;
&gt; Floating-point are messed up. The above method makes a claim about
&gt; precision that Java can&#39;t live up to. In the spirit of not promising
&gt; more than you can deliver, it&#39;s best not to use such a method. You can
&gt; always use a tolerance of 0, but be aware that it&#39;s not necessarily a
&gt; good idea.
&gt;
&gt; Oh, and if you&#39;re not doing calculations with the double values, then
&gt; why are they doubles? A BigDecimal has the added advantage of not
&gt; succumbing to the same precision problems. Maybe even a String would
&gt; do. (I hate having to hack around the language&#39;s inadequacies, but it&#39;s
&gt; a living.)
&gt;
&gt; &gt;Or would that be assertSame()?
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s only for Object identity: true if two Objects are the same part
&gt; of memory; false otherwise.
&gt;
&gt; &gt;The thing is I was testing to see if the value I put into a class was
&gt; &gt;the same I got out of a class.  There were no calculations at this
&gt; &gt;point,
&gt; &gt;where we would need to worry about the &quot;delta&quot; or +/- uncertainty.
&gt;
&gt; Then a delta of 0 would be fine. It makes it clear that you&#39;re not
&gt; expecting rounding errors to enter into the mix. That communicates
&gt; something useful.
&gt;
&gt; &gt;BTW, is there something where we can easily test asymetrical
&gt; &gt;uncertainties?
&gt; &gt;You know, something along the lines of +.5/-.1 ?
&gt;
&gt; Not built in to JUnit, but it&#39;s easy enough to build...
&gt;
&gt; assertWithinRange(final double expected, final double actual, final
&gt; double upperTolerance, final double lowerTolerance) {
&gt;     assertTrue( actual &gt;= expected - lowerTolerance && actual &lt;=
&gt; expected + upperTolerance);
&gt; }
